Plus, lots of companies won't go into a WeWork. They want their own space, their own identity; older executives may also hate the atmosphere and the Spotify hits pounding from the speakers overhead. So you lose a big chunk of potential customers that way.

If you've ever rented short-term office space, you know the process (and the spaces) are boring. It takes time and money to build out even something pretty barren. That's what makes the WeWork idea interesting. But like Uber, you can't have that model at that price point...

But during that tenure, I saw why WeWork is flailing now: the space is exciting. There's free beer! Activities! Breakfast! All the neon signage and chic photos of a boutique European hotel! And all that, of course, is a problem when you're trying to keep your costs down...

So I spent three months in a WeWork while waiting for a new office to be renovated/updated. It was a perfectly fine experience, although I missed my standing desk, and I found the beer-fueled antics of our sketchy startup-bro neighbors irritating. 1/x

(5/6) But what are some similarities between Uber and WeWork? a. City-by-city launches b. Infamous cultures c. Bad PR d. Blue-chip investors that need liquidity e. Tough CAC / LTV ratios (for now) f. a worldwide network of smaller, but aggressive copycat competitors

(4/6) 5. TK was famously against an IPO at the stage Uber was at. AFAIK Benchmark/SoftBank disagreed, and TK's ouster arguably led to the IPO. Though it is hard to say what would have happened if TK stayed. For WeWork, SoftBank may instead move to *prevent* an IPO that AN wants.

(3/6) 4. POOL, ATG, EATS, and FREIGHT are already changing unit economics and opening new revenue streams. WeWork hasn't evolved much. WeLive and WeGrow are unproven. The promise of bundling deals or being the operating system for the office has largely been unrealized.

(2/6) 3. TK never sold secondary *as CEO.*. AN did. Only after being forced out, TK did take some money off of the table to help scale his next company--City Storage Systems. OTOH AN has done many things to put WeWork money into his family's bank accounts.

(1/6) People keep comparing Uber to WeWork re SoftBank, governance, and IPO plans. They actually have little in common: 1. Uber is a high-tech business. WeWork isn't. 2. Uber avoids capex/long commitments. WeWork's business is arbitrage between long-term and short-term leases.
